Re: Not sure if I got this right...
by ThePacster » Wed 03.24.2010 10:06 am If I'm not mistaken, (verb)ことにする is used to say a decision has been made, with the の? on the end being sort of an explanation marker similar to んです.So, 「大学に行くことにしたの？」 is asking, "Has going to college been decided?"
ThePacster
Posts: 124Joined: Wed 06.07.2006 11:54 am
Top
Re: Not sure if I got this right...
by chikara » Wed 03.24.2010 8:50 pm ThePacster wrote:If I'm not mistaken, (verb)ことにする is used to say a decision has been made .... You're not mistaken. To quote A Dictionary Of Basic Japanese Grammar,ことにする - a volitional decision to do something is made. Decide to.ThePacster wrote:..... with the の? on the end being sort of an explanation marker similar to んです.So, 「大学に行くことにしたの？」 is asking, "Has going to college been decided?"That is my understanding.
Don't complain to me that people kick you when you're down. It's your own fault for lying there
